sec.p:
Functional categories encompass parts of speech belonging to different lexical categories, governed by either a verb or a noun. Both adverbal and adnominal items are sub-grouped according to the lexical category to which they can be ascribed. The listed types of adverbals are affixes (cf. apo- and ex- ‘from’ preverbs, respectively for AG and Latin), verb particles (to go in / out
) and adverbs (to go homewards
); whereas the adnominal loci identified for Path encoding are bare cases (cf. plain dative in AG or plain ablative in Latin for the expression of location), adpositions (
from


the room, into the wood), cases plus adposition (cf. Goal-oriented prepositions es and ad, respectively for AG and Latin, governing nouns in the accusative case), and localization nouns (at the top of, to the side of). Both functional categories can be further indexed in order to specify if a type of Ground (Source, Median, Goal) is overtly expressed along with Path.

In the above cases, the additional segments are placed on the left margin of the reflexes of Latin ubi ‘where’ and unde ‘whence’. The recurrent element is the voiced denti-alveolar plosive /d/, which can be identified easily as the reduced form of the ablative preposition de ‘from’ in front of a vowel-initial complement.8 Throughout our Romance sample, ablative prepositions (de, di, da, din, etc., cf. Appendix 2–4) are generally employed for the construction of spatial interrogatives of Source. This is not only the case in Asturian d'u ‘whence’ and Genovese de dove ‘whence’ but also in the remaining forty-three Romance varieties we have looked at (such as e.g. Limousin [
d{onte}unde
]whence, Moldavian [
de {unde}unde
]whence, Sicilian [
r{unni}unde
]whence (with r- < di ‘from’), Gascon [
d{on}unde
]whence ‘whence’, etc.). There is not a single exception to the following general observation: each and every spatial interrogative of Source is expressed by a construction which involves an ablative preposition, be it synchronically or diachronically. It follows from this observation that the successors of Latin unde ‘whence’ are no longer sufficient to function as spatial interrogatives of Source on their own. The employment of multi-word constructions may be interpreted as an indicator of an increasing analyticity (Kramer 2004).

Asturian ande ‘where, whither’ and Piemontese anté ‘where, whither’ are only two examples among a total of eighteen Romance varieties which, superficially, seem to attest bare successors of Latin unde ‘whence’ in the function of spatial interrogative of Place and/or Goal, i.e., the spatial interrogative which originally fulfilled the task of expressing Source resulted in an unexpected syncretism of Source and Goal, which was probably the reason for the introduction of new encoding strategies for Source (as e.g. Gallurese [{undi}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ vs [
da {undi}unde
]whence ‘whence’). However, at least some of those spatial interrogatives whose initial segment is /a/ might ultimately go back to the coalescence of the preposition a ‘at, to’ with the first vowel of the spatial interrogative. The Extremaduran minimal pair ondi ‘where’ vs andi ‘whither’ (< a + ondi) is a case in point. Galician (Carballo Calero 1979) and Portuguese onde ‘where’ vs a onde ‘whither’ are representative of the diachronic stage that preceded the fusion of preposition and spatial interrogative in Extremaduran. It is therefore possible to reanalyze Asturian ande ‘where, whither’ as [
a{nde}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’. Similarly, Piemontese anté ‘where, whither’ could be given a (historically) bimorphemic interpretation as [
a{nté}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’. This hypothesis is supported by evidence from Gascon (Romieu & Bianchi 1995) and Aranese where the spatial interrogative of Place is [
a {on}unde
]where ‘where’. In Catalan [
a {on(t)}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ (Brumme 1997) is a construction that alternates with its prepositionless competitor [{on(t)}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ vs [
d{on(t)}unde
]whence ‘whence’. Thus, additional (i.e., etymologically unjustified) segmental material shows up in the paradigms under scrutiny outside the domain of the spatial interrogative of Source.9 Since Classical Latin did not employ prepositions to construe spatial interrogatives, all of these cases can be considered to be Romance innovations.

Except Asturian, all the Romance varieties of our sample that employ a successor of Latin unde ‘whence’ in the constructions of their spatial interrogatives of Place and/or Goal also employ a reflex of Latin unde ‘whence’ for the expression of Source. In Asturian, [
a{nde}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ combines with [
d{ú}ubi
]whence ‘whence’ so that the modern distribution of the spatial interrogatives is the exact inversion of the situation in classical Latin. Wherever there is a bare reflex of Latin unde ‘whence’ in the Romance varieties, its function is never that of Source.

That we are dealing with a cyclic process receives support from the even more impressive parallel of the second set of spatial interrogatives of Genovese. This second set illustrates the generalization of Latin ubi ‘where’ over the entire paradigm since we find the etymological successor of the Latin spatial interrogative in all the cells of the paradigm, namely [
d{ove}ubi
]where=whither‘where, whither’ and [
de | d{ove}ubi
]whence ‘whence’. The symbol | separates two layers that reflect processes of reinforcement that happened at different points of the diachronic development of the variety under scrutiny. These constructions are indicative of multiple successive processes of neutralization and renovation that went to and fro between Place and Source, as shown in Table 11.

Reinforcement and renovation are commonplace within Romance. A striking example of the predilection for reinforcement and renovation is provided by Romanian. Romanian has two spatial interrogatives of Source, viz. the (unspectacular) PP [
de {unde}unde
]whence ‘whence’ and dincotro ‘whence’ – a construction that, superficially, seems to be based on elements from outside the paradigm itself. However, the latter can be shown to result from a combination of Latin de ‘from’ + in ‘in’ + contra ‘against’ + ubi ‘where’, meaning: it is a three times reinforced original ubi ‘where’ so that [
d|in|cotr{o}ubi
]whence ‘whence’ is the correct form of representation according to the principles we have introduced above. [
în|cotr{o}ubi
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ functions as an allomorph of [{unde}unde
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ in the domain of Place and Goal (Iordan & Robu 1978: 508). This means that ablative prepositions do not have the monopoly of being susceptible to reinforcement.

In point of fact, there is evidence that Romance prepositions which connect diachronically to Latin ad ‘to’, contra ‘against’, in ‘in, at’, and (late Latin) per ‘through, by, for’ are employed for the purpose of renovating the spatial interrogatives. In Table 9, the Piemontese spatial interrogative of Place is telling: the construction [
an|d{oa}ubi
]where can be decomposed into three components. There is the etymologically basic *{oa}ubi
 which continues Latin ubi ‘where’. This component, however, cannot occur on its own any more. It is preceded obligatorily by the residual consonant /d/ of the ablative preposition de ‘from’ to yield [
d{oa}ubi
]whither, which is the word-form of the spatial interrogative of Goal. It suggests that at some point in the history of Piemontese this construction was in charge of expressing Source. We assume that a succession of processes similar to those reconstructed for Genovese in Tables 10–11 has affected the older system of Piemontese spatial interrogatives so that *[
d{oa}ubi
]whence diffused into the cells of Place and Goal. Two further processes blocked the complete neutralization of all paradigmatic distinctions. These processes are: the deletion of the generalized construction from the domain of Source (where [
d{anté}unde
]whence could take over) took place and subsequently or simultaneously, the reinforcement of the spatial interrogative of Place took place. This was achieved by way of adding the preposition in (> an-) to the otherwise indistinct construction in order to keep it formally distinct from the spatial interrogative of Goal. In the course of these compensatory processes the spatial interrogative of Goal assumed the status of the least marked member of the paradigm because [an|d{oa}ubi]where displays the highest degree of complexity of the word-forms of the paradigm whereas [
d{anté}unde
]whence is suppletive and thus relatively marked within the paradigm.

In Bolognese, reinforcement via the addition of the preposition in also comes to the fore. However, in this Romance variety the spatial interrogative of Place is exempt from being renovated twice. Bolognese attests to the generalization of ubi ‘where’ over the paradigm of spatial interrogatives. The chain of segments shared by all members of the paradigm is [
d{uv}ubi
]where=whither ‘where, whither’ which is identical to the syncretic spatial interrogative of Place and Goal. The initial /d/ is again a residue of the ablative preposition de ‘from’. This is why we assume a diachronic scenario which is largely analogous to the one we have postulated for Genovese in Table 11. After the generalization of ubi, the spatial interrogative of Source was reinforced by de ‘from’. The reinforced construction spread into the domain of the spatial interrogatives of Place and Goal so that the neutralization of the spatial categories became a possibility. To prevent neutralization from taking effect, the spatial interrogative of Goal was optionally supplemented by the preposition in whereas this increment was blocked in the case of the spatial interrogative of Place. If we discount the possibility that the formal identity of the expressions of Place and Source represents the more plausible scenario, it can be speculated that the same preposition then spread from the cell of Goal to that of Source so that temporarily there was no distinction between these two dynamic spatial relations and *[
in|d{uv}ubi
]whither=whence came to function as a spatial interrogative of both Goal and Source. A third reinforcement facilitated the disambiguation of the two functions. The ablative preposition de ‘from’ was added to the ambiguous construction to yield [
d|in|d{uv}ubi
]whence as a new spatial interrogative of Source. Parallel processes can be assumed for

