A residual initial nasal plays a role in two other cases. In Provençal II, the spatial interrogative of Place [{ounte}unde
]where, has the allomorph [
m{ounte}unde
]where=whither, that is syncretic with the spatial interrogative of Goal. The initial bilabial nasal /m/ is also part of the construction of the spatial interrogative of Source, which is [
de | m{ounte}unde
]whence. To our mind, it is very likely that this nasal segment goes back diachronically to the final consonant of a spatial preposition – most probably a variant of in. If this is true, Provençal II reflects a diachronic development that is relatively similar to that of Bolognese (cf. above) albeit on the basis of Latin unde in lieu of Latin ubi. Sardinian (Blasco Ferrer 1986) illustrates Pattern I with three formally distinct constructions in the paradigm of spatial interrogatives: Place = [
in{ue}ubi
]where vs Goal = [
a | n{ue}ubi
]whither vs Source = [
da | n{ue}ubi
]whence. All these three constructions testify to renovation. In the case of Goal and Source it can be assumed that the constructions were reinforced twice after the first internal syllable boundary in the phonological chain /i.nu.e/ was reanalzyed as morpheme boundary so that /nue/ was taken to be the Q-stem.

The preposition a is also attested as reinforcement of spatial-interrogative constructions outside the Sardinian context. Apart from Spanish [
a|d{onde}unde
]whither, Portuguese and Galician [
a{onde}unde
]whither and similar cases from the Iberian Peninsula, this preposition also shows up in Gascon and Aranese (cf. above in this Section). Their close genetic relation notwithstanding, the two Romance varieties provide evidence of variation. In Gascon, the renovating preposition a is limited to the expression of Place: Place = [
a {on}unde
]where vs Goal = [{on}unde
]whither vs Source = [
d{on}unde
]whence. The constructions of the spatial interrogatives of Place and Source can be derived directly from that of Goal. This can be taken as evidence of the unmarked status of Goal in the paradigm of spatial interrogatives of Gascon. As to the situation in Aranese, the facts look different. Each of the three constructions bears the mark of renovation. The preposition a turns up in the constructions employed for Place (= [
a {on}unde
]where) and Source (= [
d|a {on}unde
]whence) with the latter being reinforced twice – the second time on the basis of the spatial interrogative of Place. The spatial interrogative of Goal, however, involves the allative preposition (en)tà ‘to’ (= [
tà {on}unde
]whither), which is also attested in Aragonese [
ta | d{ó}ubi
]whither (besides [
d{o}ubi
]where and [d{án}unde]whence).

To round off the empirical part of this study, we touch upon further cases cursorily in which the original Latin spatial interrogatives have undergone reinforcement of some kind. In Neapolitan (Fierro 1989), the prepositions a and ad are the most likely candidates for the status of renovators in the syncretic construction of the spatial interrogatives of Place and Goal [ad|d{o’}ubi
]where=whither. The geminated dental plosive may either connect to the Latin preposition ad or result from raddoppiamento fonosintattico after a. The spatial interrogative of Source contains a reduced (= aphaeretic) reflex of the ablative preposition da ‘from’, as can be gathered from [
‘a | d{o’}ubi
]whence. In sum, the Neapolitan spatial interrogatives have been renovated twice.

One of the allomorphs of the spatial interrogative of Goal in Portuguese, Galician, and Extremaduran relates historically to Latin per, namely in Portuguese and Galician [
para {onde}unde
]whither and Extremaduran [p’a{óndi}unde]whither. In addition to the prepositional renovators, the Picardian spatial interrogatives host the French interrogative marker est-ce que as in: Place-Goal = [
d{ù}ubi
sque
]where=whither vs Source [
ed|d{ù}ubi
sque
]whence (ed < de ‘from’). Double reinforcement applies to the Picardian spatial interrogative of Source.
